<div class='panel learn-more'>
<div class='argument-column con-column'>
<div class='title'>
Con
</div>
<a name='argument-217'></a>
<div class='argument' data-id='217'>
<div class='header'>
<a href=""><img alt="Unknown-tiny" class="created-by-image" src="/images/unknown-tiny.png?1330528636" />
</a><div class='header-right'>
<a href="" class="created-by-name">Karl</a>
<div class='cred-score'>
45
cred
</div>
</div>
<div class='clear'></div>
<div class='created-at'>Dec 04, 2011</div>
</div>
<div class='argument-text'>
Income is income. Investors do not need an incentive for long-term investment, which is what the capital gains tax is meant to induce. If an investment provides a good return, it will attract capital. (Plus, the idea of one year as the definition of &quot;long term&quot; is laughable.)<br/><br/>By treating all income equally, the very wealthy, who have tailored their investments to favor capital gains, would pay their fair share. (This is the Buffett logic...which is totally correct.)
</div>
